page.title: 09Southern Nazeing 3: Wildlife
page.content: The lakes also attract a tremendous variety of wildlife. On our excursions a number of birds could be identified, eg Moorhens, Cootes, Swans, Herons, Swallows, Wagtails to name but a few. During the summer months a whole variety of insects can be observed and surely none more beautiful than the Damson Fly performing its aquatic dance over the river. This part of the area is one which has tremendous potential as a leisure facility - what we are witnessing at present is the 'infant' stage. One feature that does rather scar the landscape are the overhead transmission lines that come from the power station in Hoddesden and "march" across the countryside carrying the much needed electricity to the Urban and industrial areas surrounding Nazeing.
